<author><name><![CDATA[tepples]]></name></author>
<updated>2015-02-25T18:00:14-07:00</updated>
<published>2015-02-25T18:00:14-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12431&amp;p=142082#p142082</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12431&amp;p=142082#p142082"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Re: Duplicating data on SNES games for bigger memories]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=12431&amp;p=142082#p142082"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">MaarioS wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />This was always a mystery for me: why do you need to duplicate the game data if you want to program it on a bigger memory??<br /></div><br />You have to either duplicate it or connect the memory's high address lines to ground. For example, to put a 1 MB game on a 4 MB memory, you would ground A20 and A21 on the memory and leave A20 and A21 (HiROM) or A21 and A22 (LoROM) on the cart disconnected.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />why the hell do you need to do that, what's the point of this?? The last 2MB of memory should never be triggered at all since there's no point of that<br /></div><br />You'd be surprised at how many games rely on the entire memory being mirrored. <em>Mega Man X</em> is 1.25 MB and will break early on if you don't properly duplicate the last .25 MB four times.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />But how about if I have a game that is 2,5MB, so..... what should I do about it?? Duplicate the last 3/8 (1,5MB) of data or last 0,5MB * 3??<br /></div><br />A 2.5 MB game like <em>Street Fighter II Turbo</em> is stored on two chips. The first is 2 MB and the second is .5 MB. So to put it on one chip, you'd mirror the last .5 MB up to 4 MB.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Wed Feb 25, 2015 6:00 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
